      "text": "Picture willpower as holding your breath. Through sheer effort you can do it for a while — but the moment your attention drops, the held breath bursts out. That's the structure of every willpower quit: you want a cigarette and you simply forbid yourself one. You've created a permanent state of deprivation and assigned yourself the impossible job of enduring it forever.\n\nThe fatal flaw is that the wanting is left fully intact. So you spend the day in a tug-of-war with yourself, white-knuckling, waiting for the desire to fade. But desire that's resisted doesn't fade — it's fed by the resistance. The more you fixate on not smoking, the more precious the cigarette becomes, until a stressful day, a drink, or a celebration tips you over, and the held breath bursts. Then you conclude \"I don't have the willpower,\" when the truth is that willpower was never the right tool. You can't out-muscle a desire forever. You have to remove it. That's the entire point of these ten days — and why, by Day 10, putting the cigarette down will feel like relief, not deprivation."
