      "text": "Cutting down sounds reasonable — fewer is better, surely a stepping stone to none. In practice it's a trap that can hold people for life. Here's the mechanism:\n\nWhen you stretch the gap between cigarettes, you spend more of your day in active withdrawal — that low, restless itch — instead of relieving it promptly as you used to. So you're more uncomfortable, not less. And the longer you make yourself wait, the more relief each cigarette delivers when you finally allow it, which makes each one feel more precious, not less. You're literally training yourself to treasure the very thing you're trying to escape. Cutting down teaches your brain that the cigarette is the most valuable thing in your day.\n\nIt also relies on the same exhausting willpower you've just seen is finite — except now you have to ration and resist every single day, forever. If you didn't have enough willpower to stop, you certainly won't sustain a lifetime of disciplined rationing. Cutting down keeps the little monster alive in your body and the big monster — the belief — alive and growing in your mind. It is, reliably, the long way back to where you started."
